    <title>Combined summary - The insecurity of merge-mining</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T23:23:21.785382+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-January/004008.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Peter Todd and Luke-Jr discussed merged mining, altcoin security, and vulnerability to attacks. Todd was concerned about non-majority crypto-currencies using merged mining being at risk of 51% attacks from attackers. He also proposed a merge-mined Zerocoin implementation with a 1:1 BTC/ZTC exchange rate enforced by the software. Luke-Jr believed that any non-scam altcoin is pretty safe using merged mining since it is in the attacker's interests to invest in the altcoin instead of attacking it. The discussion also touched on decentralized consensus systems competing for market share, with Todd using the example of Namecoin miners potentially attacking a new blockchain to protect their own interests and investments. Merge-mined alt-coins that are currencies often get attacked quickly as they dilute the value of existing coins. However, there were other reasons why some currencies that died with merged mining (MM) and others survived.Todd and Jorge Timón discussed the profitability of mining a cryptocurrency and the security mechanisms in merged mining. They then questioned the usefulness and value of a secure chain compared to a less secure one. Timón expressed doubts about the proof-of-sacrifice as a security mechanism and the viability of proof-of-sacrificed-zerocoins.Peter Todd wrote about the situation with the new Twister P2P Microblogging thing that has a blockchain for registering usernames. He said that this could have been easily done with Namecoin which means that Namecoin owners have an incentive to make sure the Twister blockchain gets killed at birth. However, merging mining could be a solution. If they start with SHA256, then merged mining is a trivial fork that has been successfully done by at least 3 currencies.In general, if a new system has greater value than the harm done to participants in the old system, it has a chance of surviving. Rational bitcoin miners should mine Namecoin, and those who consider it competition with their current Bitcoin speculative position should sell the Namecoins as soon as they get them. Providing security for a chain does not give it utility or raise its demand.</summary>
